1. Plugins

Note: this covers only the Qt project's own plugins, not user/application
plugins.

Plugins are usually shared libraries that are loaded at runtime.

The plugin implements a single public Qt interface such as
QPlatformIntegrationPlugin, QPlatformInputContextPlugin, or QImageIOPlugin.

Typically in <pluginname>main.{h,cpp}, the main plugin class uses the
Q_PLUGIN_METADATA macro which causes moc to generate (via the
QT_MOC_EXPORT_PLUGIN macro) the functions qt_plugin_instance() and
qt_plugin_query_metadata() (in addition to other plugin and general
infrastructure boilerplate).

qt_plugin_instance() returns a pointer to one of the Qt interface classes
which references an instance of the plugin's implementation class.

As one might expect based on the above design, none of the plugin's code,
including the class which implements the Qt interface class, is exported.
Only the qt_plugin_instance() and qt_plugin_query_metadata() functions are
exported.

1.1 Macros

QT_PLUGIN is defined when a plugin is being built; rarely used.

1.2 Debugging the plugin machinery

Set the environment variable QT_DEBUG_PLUGINS to 1 for detailed debug output
at runtime.
